{"type":"message","id":"0884282f","parentId":"f10e014b","timestamp":"2026-03-26T02:45:20.757Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We have a user request: \"buka browser brave dan buka youtube\" meaning \"open brave browser and open youtube\". We need to perform a tool call to open a browser and navigate to youtube. According to tools, there's a \"browser\" tool that can control the browser via OpenClaw's browser control server (status/start/stop/profiles/tabs/open/snapshot/screenshot/actions). The user says to open the brave browser and go to youtube. So we need to use the browser tool with appropriate action.\n\nThe \"browser\" tool's action enumeration includes: [\"status\", \"start\", \"stop\", \"profiles\", \"tabs\", \"open\", \"focus\", \"close\", \"snapshot\", \"screenshot\", \"navigate\", \"console\", \"pdf\", \"upload\", \"dialog\"].\n\nTo open a URL, we likely need to use \"navigate\" action. The \"navigate\" action probably requires parameters like \"url\". The \"open\" action maybe used to open a new tab? Let's examine the tool definition:\n\nThe \"browser\" tool takes parameters: action (string, one of those), target (sandbox|host|node), node (string), profile (string), targetUrl (string), url (string), targetId (string), ... many options.\n\nTo open a URL in the browser, we probably need to use \"navigate\" action with \"url\" parameter specifying the target URL. There may also be \"open\" action? In the enumeration, \"open\" appears as an action. It might be used to open a new tab or open the browser? Let's read the description: \"Control the browser via OpenClaw's browser control server (status/start/stop/profiles/tabs/open/snapshot/screenshot/actions). Browser choice: omit profile by default for the isolated OpenClaw-managed browser (`openclaw`). For the logged-in user browser on the local host, use profile=\"user\". A supported Chromium-based browser (v144+) must be running. Use only when existing logins/cookies matter and the user is present. When a node-hosted browser proxy is available, the tool may auto-route to it. Pin a node with node=<id|name> or target=\"node\". When using refs from snapshot (e.g. e12), keep the same tab: prefer passing targetId from the snapshot response into subsequent actions (act/click/type/etc). For stable, self-resolving refs across calls, use snapshot with refs=\"aria\" (Playwright aria-ref ids). Default refs=\"role\" are role+name-based. Use snapshot+act for UI automation. Avoid act:wait by default; use only in exceptional cases when no reliable UI state exists. target selects browser location (sandbox|host|node). Default: host. Host target allowed.\"\n\nThe \"open\" action probably is used to open the browser, maybe start a new tab. But likely the correct approach: we need to start a browser session (maybe \"start\" action) then \"navigate\" to youtube. But it's also possible to directly \"navigate\" to a URL, which may implicitly start the browser if not started. The \"navigate\" action likely used to navigate a given tab to a URL.\n\nSince the user specifically says \"buka browser brave dan buka youtube\". We may need to start the brave browser. However, the system may have a default browser configured (maybe \"brave\").\n\nThe \"browser\" tool's profile parameter can specify a profile name. The default for isolated browser is \"openclaw\". For logged-in user profile \"user\". Brave might be a separate profile. But I'm not sure if there is a pre-configured profile for Brave. Perhaps the system has a list of browsers we can target: \"sandbox\" (isolated), \"host\" (host OS), \"node\" (node). The Brave browser may be running as a host application, so we might use target=\"host\" and profile maybe \"brave\" or something else.\n\nBut the tool signature: \"profile\" is a string, optional. It says \"omit profile by default for the isolated OpenClaw-managed browser (`openclaw`). For the logged-in user browser on the local host, use profile=\"user\".\"\n\nSo if we want to open the \"brave\" browser, maybe there is a profile name for it. Possibly it's just \"brave\". But not sure.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we simply call \"navigate\" with \"url\" set to \"https://youtube.com\" and that will open the browser automatically.\n\nBetter to check the tool's description: It can perform \"navigate\" action. Example usage: we might do:\n\n{\n  \"action\": \"navigate\",\n  \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\",\n  \"target\": \"host\",\n  \"profile\": \"user\"\n}\n\nBut we need to see what fields are required. The \"action\" is required. \"target\" optional? The tool definition shows many possible parameters but no explicit required list except \"action\". So we can supply any needed ones.\n\nThus, we could possibly just call:\n\n{\n  \"action\": \"navigate\",\n  \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\"\n}\n\nThat might open the browser (or a new tab) and navigate to youtube.\n\nBut the user also wants to \"buka browser brave\". That implies we need to open the Brave browser specifically. Possibly we need to start a browser session with \"start\" action and specify the browser type, but not sure.\n\nThe \"browser\" tool also supports \"open\" action. Let's look at the enumeration: [\"status\", \"start\", \"stop\", \"profiles\", \"tabs\", \"open\", \"focus\", \"close\", \"snapshot\", \"screenshot\", \"navigate\", \"console\", \"pdf\", \"upload\", \"dialog\"].\n\nThe \"open\" action perhaps is used to open the browser. It might need \"profile\" param to specify which profile to open. \"target\" might specify location.\n\nThus, to fulfill the user request, we can issue two calls: \"start\" or \"open\" to start a brave browser, then \"navigate\" to youtube. However, maybe a single \"navigate\" action will open the browser automatically if it's not already open.\n\nWe need to think about the best approach to ensure we meet the user's request. Also need to follow policy about using tools: we can only make one tool call per turn. So we need to decide which tool call to make. The user wants to open Brave and go to youtube. Probably the easiest: call browser with action=\"navigate\" and url=\"https://www.youtube.com\". That should open the browser and navigate to youtube.\n\nBut is there any need to specify target or profile? Possibly not. The default target is \"host\". That might refer to the local machine's browser. The default profile is omitted, which uses the isolated OpenClaw-managed browser (`openclaw`). That might not be Brave; it's probably some default headless browser used by OpenClaw. If we want to open Brave, maybe we need to specify a profile name that corresponds to Brave. But we may not know the profile name.\n\nMaybe there's a skill or config that maps \"brave\" as a profile name. Could be the \"browser\" tool can open any Chromium-based browser if it's installed, using the \"profile\" parameter specifying the folder name e.g., \"Brave\". But it's uncertain.\n\nAlternatively, we can spawn a new session with \"sessions_spawn\" runtime=acp or subagent to run a separate web browsing task via Playwright (there is a skill named \"Playwright (Automation + MCP + Scraper)\". That skill can control browser actions. But simpler is the \"browser\" tool.\n\nGiven that the user request is specific: \"buka browser brave dan buka youtube\". We can interpret that as \"Open the Brave browser and go to YouTube\". We need to use the browser control tool to perform this. The tool we have is \"browser\". We can use \"open\" action to launch the browser, and then \"navigate\" to youtube.\n\nBut open alone may just open a new window but not navigate. However, perhaps \"open\" action has a parameter \"url\" to open a URL directly. Let's speculate: The \"open\" action might be used to open a new tab with a given URL. It could be like \"open\" with \"url\" param to open that URL in the default browser. Or \"open\" might just open the browser UI (like open a window) and we need to subsequently \"navigate\".\n\nThe tool description doesn't provide usage details for each action. It just enumerates actions and parameters. The \"open\" action probably opens a new tab/window. It might require \"url\". However, there is also \"navigate\" which is explicitly for navigating to a URL.\n\nThus, possibly we can do a single \"navigate\" action to youtube, and it will open the browser if needed. That would satisfy the request. The user didn't explicitly request to open a new tab if one exists; just \"buka browser brave dan buka youtube\". So navigates to youtube will implicitly open the browser.\n\nThus, I think we can do a tool call:\n\n{\n  \"action\": \"navigate\",\n  \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\"\n}\n\nMaybe also include \"target\": \"host\" to use the host's browser. Or maybe specify \"profile\": \"brave\" if needed. But we can keep it simple.\n\nBut before calling, check any policies: The user explicitly wants to open a browser to YouTube. That's benign. No policy violation. Use tool call, not message. So we can proceed with a tool call.\n\nThus, I'll call the \"browser\" tool with \"navigate\" action and \"url\" set to \"https://www.youtube.com\". Likely we need to use the \"browser\" tool with \"action\": \"navigate\", \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\". Possibly also need \"target\": \"host\". But we can leave unspecified; default is \"host\". So send the tool call accordingly.\n\nThus, the tool call would be:\n\n{\n  \"action\": \"navigate\",\n  \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\"\n}\n\nAlternatively, we might need to use \"open\" action:\n\n{\n  \"action\": \"open\",\n  \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\"\n}\n\nBut uncertain which action is appropriate. Looking at the action enumeration: \"open\", \"navigate\". The \"open\" action might be used to open a new tab/window, while \"navigate\" is to navigate currently opened tab. If we want to open Brave and then go to youtube, we probably need to \"open\" the browser first, then \"navigate\". But maybe \"navigate\" automatically opens the browser. In typical browsers, navigating to a URL loads it in the current tab; if no tab is open, it might open a new one.\n\nGiven that the tool is called \"browser control server (status/start/stop/profiles/tabs/open/snapshot/screenshot/actions)\", the \"open\" action likely opens a new tab/window, while \"navigate\" navigates a tab. Possibly \"open\" has a parameter \"url\". Alternatively, \"open\" might just open the browser UI, not a specific URL.\n\nBut the enumeration includes \"tabs\" as an action as well. Maybe \"tabs\" lists open tabs, and \"open\" opens a new tab with a given URL.\n\nGiven we lack clarity, but we need to act. The simplest that aligns with typical usage: Use \"navigate\" to load youtube. That probably suffices.\n\nThus, call:\n\n{\n  \"action\": \"navigate\",\n  \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com\"\n}\n\nMake sure to include the required fields: \"action\" must be a string matching defined action name. \"url\" is probably required for navigate. There's no other required fields.\n\nThus, call that.\n\nProceed to call the tool.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ee7de9ead1e044dcbb4ebefc","name":"browser","arguments":{"target":"host","profile":"brave","action":"navigate","url":"https://www.youtube.com"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-nano-30b-a3b:free","usage":{"input":21581,"output":5285,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":26866,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774493105483,"responseId":"gen-1774493105-hMrment8bUi15LtzqFEh"}}
