text of openclaw, the typical approach for \"open browser\" tasks is indeed to use the \"browser\" tool. However, if that fails due to missing browser or failing to attach, we can inform the user that the browser is not available or we cannot open it right now.\n\nWe must not fabricate steps or give false info. We need to be truthful: we attempted to open Brave, got errors, restarted gateway, but still couldn't attach. So maybe it's best to tell the user that the browser is currently unavailable.\n\nHowever, we have the \"exec\" tool that can execute shell commands. Could we use it to open Brave?\n\nThe tool \"exec\" can run any shell command. We can try \"start \"\" \"https://www.youtube.com\"\" which will open the default browser to YouTube. That might not be Brave specifically, but it will open a browser window. If we want Brave specifically, we can try to run the path to Brave if known. Typically on Windows, the Brave binary is at something like \"C:\\Program Files\\BraveSoftware\\Brave-Browser\\Application\\brave.exe\". If that path exists, we can run it with the URL as an argument: \"brave.exe https://www.youtube.com\". However we cannot guarantee that path exists. We can try \"where brave\" to locate it. But \"where\" is a cmd command; we can exec that.\n\nBut we need to follow the policies: If we need to run a command that might not be present, we can test it. Use exec to try to start it; if it fails, we can handle. However, we need to request approval if the command might cause side effects? No special restrictions apply; opening a browser is benign. So we can proceed to exec.\n\nBut perhaps it's better to check if the \"brave\" command is available via \"where brave\". Let's try \"exec\" with command \"where brave\". Use \"exec\" with \"command\": \"where brave\". That will output the path if found, or nothing if not. Then we can maybe use that path to start brave.\n\nAlternatively, we can exec \"start brave https://www.youtube.com\". Actually the \"start\" command in Windows can launch URLs with associated apps. \"start brave https://www.youtube.com\" would try to open a file named \"brave\" with the URL as an argument; if a file named brave is not found, it might try to auto-associate the \"brave\" verb with something else. Typically \"start\" uses the default program associated with .url? But \"start\" can also launch an executable by name. Better is to directly call the exe path.\n\nBut perhaps easier is to use \"start \"\" \"https://www.youtube.com\"\" which uses the default handler, which is probably Edge or Chrome. That might not be Brave. However, the user explicitly said Brave. If Brave is set as the default browser, then \"start \"\" \"https://www.youtube.com\"\" would open Brave. We could check the default browser via the registry or command \"assoc .htm\"? Not sure.\n\nGiven the constraints, it's probably best to attempt to use \"exec\" to open the URL in the default browser, and mention that if they specifically need Brave, they may need to ensure it's installed and default. Alternatively, we can ask the user if they want to open it in the default browser.\n\nBut the user explicitly wants Brave. We could try to open Brave by path. Let's attempt to locate Brave. There may be a typical install path: \"C:\\Program Files\\BraveSoftware\\Brave-Browser\\Application\\brave.exe\". Let's exec \"cmd /c dir /b \\\"C:\\Program Files\\BraveSoftware\\Brave-Browser\\Application\\brave.exe\\\"\" or \"ls\". Actually exec can run \"powershell\" commands too? The default shell is powershell based on the config: shell=powershell. So we can run PowerShell commands.\n\nWe could exec \"powershell -Command \\\"if (Test-Path 'C:\\\\Program Files\\\\BraveSoftware\\\\Brave-Browser\\\\Application\\\\brave.exe') { 'found' } else { 'not found' }\\\"\". That will return \"found\" or \"not found\". Let's try that.\n\nBut before calling exec we need to decide what command to run exactly. The \"exec\" tool takes a shell command string; it runs it in a shell. It can be any command that the host's shell can interpret. Provide \"command\": \"powershell -Command \\\"(Get-Item 'C:\\\\Program Files\\\\BraveSoftware\\\\Brave-Browser\\\\Application\\\\brave.exe' -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue).Exists\\\"\". That returns True/False. We can capture output.\n\nBut the \"exec\" tool returns the output? It may return the command execution result as \"data\"? The specification says \"exec\" returns ... but not clearly what is returned. It can be used to start a process; maybe it returns some result. Possibly we need to use \"process\" tool to manage interactive sessions. However, \"exec\" can run a command, but how do we get its output? The \"exec\" tool may simply execute and return an \"ok\" with some data. In previous uses, they used \"exec\" to run a command and got \"ok\": true with some details like pid. It might not output stdout. Usually to run a command and get output, we might use \"exec\" with \"background\": false? Or maybe we can use \"process\" to spawn a shell and send commands. But easier may be to just try to launch the browser using \"exec\" and not worry about capturing output.\n\nBut perhaps more appropriate is to use \"exec\" with \"command\": \"start brave https://www.youtube.com\". Let's try that.\n\nBut before that, let's verify if brave exists. Use \"exec\" command: \"powershell -Command \\\"(Get-Process brave -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue).Path\\\"\". Actually \"Get-Process\" may be more reliable. Or \"Test-Path\". Let's just try to start it directly: \"start \\\"\\\" \\\"brave.exe\\\" https://www.youtube.com\"? Not sure.\n\nActually the command to open a URL with a specific browser from the command line typically is \"brave.exe https://www.youtube.com\". If brave is in PATH, that works. Alternatively, \"start \"\" \"brave.exe\" https://www.youtube.com\"? Or \"start brave https://www.youtube.com\". The \"start\" command can take a program name and then arguments. For example: \"start bra